Do you reject conservation of mass-energy on the grounds that it is
socially undesirable?  Do you think that the US grain reserves
appeared miraculously because American farmers believed in sharing?
The paragraph above, while perhaps well-intentioned, is laughable.
Excludable property--resources that can only be used by one person
at a time--are a simple fact of objective reality, and no amount of
hand-waving and pretty prose can change that.  "Hoarding" can
exacerbate shortages, and even create them, but to think that
eliminating hoarding will eliminate all shortages is childish
fantasy.  Property rights may or may not be the best way to allocate
scarce resource; it is definitely the best one so far tried.  There
may be an even better solution, but I doubt that denying the
problem will lead to finding it.

